The Covid-19 pandemic has battered the hospitality
industry worldwide, and Malaysian hotels are expecting
the worst year in history. Data from the Malaysian
Association of Hotels (MAH), based on surveys conducted
among its members, indicates an average occupancy of
25.41% in 2020, down from 64.49% last year. This decline
is expected to lead to the sector losing RM6.36 billion in
revenue, forcing many hotels to temporarily close their
facilities or, worse, shut down permanently. Others have
resorted to reducing their room inventory, implementing
salary cuts or laying off employees. On a brighter note,
forward bookings have started coming in and demand is
seen from as early as July.
